{"title": "Microsoft backs Australia's proposed media laws targeting Google, Facebook", "text": "A Microsoft logo is seen in Los Angeles, California U.S. November 7, 2017. REUTERS/Lucy Nicholson/File Photo Feb 3 (Reuters) - Microsoft Corp   said on Wednesday it fully supported  proposed new laws in Australia that would force internet giant Google and social media heavyweight Facebook Inc   to pay domestic media outlets for their content. \"While Microsoft is not subject to the legislation currently pending, we'd be willing to live by these rules if the government designates us,\" the software giant said in a statement. Both Alphabet Inc's   Google and Facebook have called the laws unworkable and said last month they would withdraw key services from Australia if the regulations went ahead.  Our Standards:  Subscribe for our daily curated newsletter to receive the latest exclusive Reuters coverage delivered to your inbox. T-Mobile US Inc (TMUS.O) said on Wednesday an ongoing investigation into a cyberattack on its systems revealed that some personal data of about 7.8 million of its current postpaid customers were compromised. Reuters, the news and media division of Thomson Reuters, is the world\u2019s largest multimedia news provider, reaching billions of people worldwide every day. Reuters provides business, financial, national and international news to professionals via desktop terminals, the world's media organizations, industry events and directly to consumers. Build the strongest argument relying on authoritative content, attorney-editor expertise, and industry defining technology. The most comprehensive solution to manage all your complex and ever-expanding tax and compliance needs. The industry leader for online information for tax, accounting and finance professionals. Information, analytics and exclusive news on financial markets - delivered in an intuitive desktop and mobile interface. Access to real-time, reference, and non-real time data in the cloud to po